4c8.title: Log base infinity
4c8.clickbait: There is no log base infinity, but if there were, it would send everything to zero
4c8.text:
There is no $\log_{\infty},$ because $\infty$ is not a real number. Nevertheless, the function $z$ defined as $z(x) = 0$ for all $x \in$ [positive_reals $\mathbb R^+$] can pretty readily be interpreted as $\log_{\infty}$.

That is, $z$ satisfies all properties of the basic [4bz properties of the logarithm] if you squint and use your $\infty$ symbols right. Namely, if we allow $\log_\infty$ to return multiple values when its input is infinite, and we allow exponentiation to return multiple values when its base is infinite (and infinite values when its exponent is infinite), then we can define $\log_\infty$ as a [-multifunction] which is equal to $z$ whenever its input is finite. Then, if we strategically re-interpret some '$=$' signs as '[set_contains $\in$]' signs, all the basic [4bz properties of the logarithm] hold for $\log_\infty$. For example, $\log_\infty(1) = 0,$ and $1 \in \log_\infty(\infty),$ and $x \in \log_\infty(\infty ^ x),$ and $x \in \infty^{\log_\infty(x)}.$ Alternatively, if we don't allow infinite inputs to $\log_\infty,$ then it is equal to $z$ and satisfies all the properties of the logarithm _except_ for the one that says there is a base $b$ such that $\log_\infty(b) = 1.$
